headline: Nike Predicts Its Tariff Costs Will Reach $1.5 Billion for Fiscal Year
summary: Nike executives now expect the company’s tariff costs to total $1.5 billion this fiscal year, up from the $1 billion they projected three months ago.  The sneaker company said its cost of sales in the latest quarter increased 7%, or $445 million, in part because of tariffs.  “We are monitoring developments closely, and I remain confident in our ability to leverage our strengths,” said the company’s finance chief, Matt Friend.

headline: On Holding COO Sam Wenger to step down, insider Scott Maguire to take over
